Light grey breast and belly, black tail, grey wings, white supercilium, typical godwit bill.   -- (from NBB)  Hi Ken,  I guess I was the last person to report the Hudsonian Godwit on eBird, on September 24th. It took me a while to find it, so I thought I'd describe its general location in case you go up there this weekend.  I went up there on the morning of the 23rd, but immediately had to turn around and get back to SF to handle an urgent matter. On that morning there were six Pectoral Sandpipers together in the small holding pond to the north of the tracks. The Godwit was not visible from the railroad tracks and I didn't have time to look further.  I got back up there on the 24th around 9AM. The bird was NOT visible from the tracks nor the road (where construction is happening). Eventually I walked east on the tracks about 1000', past the ranch buildings. Then I cut through a break in the fence and walked south across the field. I'm not sure how cool that is, but there was a hunting regulation sign that didn't say anything against entering. The Godwit was visible after walking south a few hundred feet. It was in the farthest pond (the SE one of the pond complex) standing in a narrows area.

Observation Details: Seen at the outer 'elbow' of the marina, in a bush that often gets weird migrants.   Empid had gray head, rounded - not peaked like a Pac Slope.  Fairly long bi-colored mandible.   Solid narrow white eye-ring that did not extend into a tear-drop in the back.   White breast with some yelllowish wash.  Very white wing bars.   Noticeably short wing tips, which I regard as diagnostic.   Continuous downward tail pump (I only know of this in Gray and Pac Slope.)   Fairly long tail.   Made a dry whit call, which was not familiar to me.   Did not respond to Pac Slope playback - I did not try Gray, since I didn't want to spook it.   There is very little suitable territory here and I assume it will be a one day wonder.

Recently fledged young bird.  Family reported earlier in the day, did not see adults.  I got down to the Presidio around 5pm this evening.  With David Tomb, we were able to pretty quickly get on what appears to be a recently fledged Lawrence’s Goldfinch.  (Someone please correct me if I’m wrong!). Note the white in the tail, the yellow already coming in on the wing, the pale head and large bill - all of which I think safely separate this from the other finches.  We stayed with this bird for about ten minutes and then it flew off with another (possibly juvenile, possibly adult female.). This was at the coordinates that Lee Hong-Chang gave in the first post.  Over the next hour I was unable to get on any other LAGOs - though I heard the tinkle call a few times.  It was difficult with the high winds and the literally hundred plus House Finch, Lesser Goldfinch, juncos, song and WC sparrows, and Hooded Orioles flying around.  This area seems to be a breeding frenzy.   You should also check the trees in a little gully about 100 yards north of the spot (not accessible by any main trail) where I last heard the LAGO call.  Are there any other breeding records of this bird in San Francisco in modern times?

I found this pale empid at 37.743747, -122.414228 on the north side of Bernal Hill.  At first seeing it in only silhouette I was struck by its long thin bill and long dark tail, thought I might be looking at a gnatcatcher for a second.  Walked around to the bare tree where it was perching in the back.  Bird seemed to stick around for a couple of minutes at a time and then disappear for 10-15 minutes.   Though I assumed Gray, I ended up walking up the hill and down a treacherous, but busy, footpath over the tree so I could get better documentation.   Uniformly gray head, auricular and back with no contrast.  Whitish throat and faint yellow on belly.   From certain angles the auricular patch seemed to stand out - the lores extensive white, and has distinctive white tuft at the base of upper mandible, which I understand helps separate Gray from Dusky.   The most definitive characteristic is the oversize thin bill, black upper mandible, yellow lower slightly darker at the tip.  If not for the size of the bill I think this would be hard to separate visually from Dusky.  Head is rounded with a slight hint of a peak to the back.   Wings and tail feathers have a weathered look in the photos with spread-wings - not sure where this would be in the molt cycle, doesn't seem complete.    Wings are comparatively short, with wingtips and rest not extending as far as undertail coverts.  Tail dark.  I think the size, shape, color of bill, length of wingtips, and head shape cinch this as a Gray vs. Hammonds/Dusky.  Bird gave out a soft "chewit"-like dry whit call.  Pumped tail downward a bit, but not excessively.  I did not use playback.  Bird did not strike me as being particularly larger than the other empids.

First SF record found by Hugh Cotter 10/9/17.  Small Sparrow sized-bird appeared very tame -  observed feeding for about 15 minutes on berm on the northern side of the great field.  Appears to be a young (first fall?) female.  Numerous field marks to separate from similar Chestnut-collared.  Note large pink bill with black tip.  Pale face with plain auriculars around unremarkable ear covert.  Wide pale supercilium - overall head color somewhat reminiscent of a female House Sparrow.  Bird had a buffy collar similar to head and not "chestnut.  Notable buffy breast-plate with barely any streaking coming to a crisp transition.  Breast patch remarkably similar in shape to that of the black breast patch of an adult male McCowns.  Median coverts were darker than other feathers - good field mark, though not as dark as an immature male, led me to think this is female.  Bird in flight had wide white patches on outer rectices.  Flew short-distances (20-50 meters) at low height - unlike a LALO.  Only called in flight.  This was my #600 ABA-Continental bird!

I found this pale empid at 37.743747, -122.414228 on the north side of Bernal Hill.  At first seeing it in only silhouette I was struck by its long thin bill and long dark tail, thought I might be looking at a gnatcatcher for a second.  Walked around to the bare tree where it was perching in the back.  Bird seemed to stick around for a couple of minutes at a time and then disappear for 10-15 minutes.   Though I assumed Gray, I ended up walking up the hill and down a treacherous, but busy, footpath over the tree so I could get better documentation.   Uniformly gray head, auricular and back with no contrast.  Whitish throat and faint yellow on belly.   From certain angles the auricular patch seemed to stand out - the lores extensive white, and has distinctive white tuft at the base of upper mandible, which I understand helps separate Gray from Dusky.   The most definitive characteristic is the oversize thin bill, black upper mandible, yellow lower slightly darker at the tip.  If not for the size of the bill I think this would be hard to separate visually from Dusky.  Head is rounded with a slight hint of a peak to the back.   Wings and tail feathers have a weathered look in the photos with spread-wings - not sure where this would be in the molt cycle, doesn't seem complete.    Wings are comparatively short, with wingtips and rest not extending as far as undertail coverts.  Tail dark.  I think the size, shape, color of bill, length of wingtips, and head shape cinch this as a Gray vs. Hammonds/Dusky.  Bird gave out a soft "chewit"-like dry whit call.  Pumped tail downward a bit, but not excessively.  I did not use playback.  Bird did not strike me as being particularly larger than the other empids.

First SF record found by Hugh Cotter 10/9/17.  Small Sparrow sized-bird appeared very tame -  observed feeding for about 15 minutes on berm on the northern side of the great field.  Appears to be a young (first fall?) female.  Numerous field marks to separate from similar Chestnut-collared.  Note large pink bill with black tip.  Pale face with plain auriculars around unremarkable ear covert.  Wide pale supercilium - overall head color somewhat reminiscent of a female House Sparrow.  Bird had a buffy collar similar to head and not "chestnut.  Notable buffy breast-plate with barely any streaking coming to a crisp transition.  Breast patch remarkably similar in shape to that of the black breast patch of an adult male McCowns.  Median coverts were darker than other feathers - good field mark, though not as dark as an immature male, led me to think this is female.  Bird in flight had wide white patches on outer rectices.  Flew short-distances (20-50 meters) at low height - unlike a LALO.  Only called in flight.  This was my #600 ABA-Continental bird!

This juvenile owl was first spotted by a neighbor who found it day-roosting in a street tree on Alabama Street on July 31st.   I went to look for it the next morning, but it was not seen again for several days.  Quite surprisingly the owl returned to the exact same spot on August 5th when I was able to see and photograph it.  The bird appears to be in juvenile plumage, with fresh crisp feathers pre-molt.  It stayed immobilized about 10' off of the sidewalk in a dark spot in the tree.  Surprisingly there do not appear to be any summer records in eBird of Saw-whets, only winter sightings ranging from 11/13 to 4/09.  Hard to say whether this bird bred locally or is ranging widely post-dispersal.   Saw-whets breed on the peninsula, starting at La Honda - but maybe closer in the Crystal Springs watershed (?), as well as to the north at Mt Tam and in small numbers in the Berkeley Hills.  Do juveniles typically wander 20+ miles prior to molt and feed on their own?  And would it stay in place for at least six days?  It seems equally likely that there was an undetected successful nesting in the general area.  There are mature trees in the neighborhood, but no closed canopy forest.  Mystery worth considering, especially if this bird shows up again.

Locality: Alviso Marina County Park (please use a specific pond hotspot where possible)
Observation Details: The Little Stint was associating with a small group of Western Sandpipers and Dunlins, and not with Least Sandpipers.  It is about the size of a Least Sandpiper - considerably smaller than a Western.   The bill is short and slightly drooped with a distinct gape notch.   The legs are black and completely unwebbed (un-palmated).  They appear long relative to body size.  The most striking diagnostic feature are the rich rufous edges on the tertials that are coming in, along with one or two rufous scapulars.  The feathers have a black shaft and rufous edging.  Otherwise the bird was much greyer than the Western Sandpipers.    The scapulars have a solid blackish appearance.  The face has a "split" supercilium that I understand distinguishes it from the other stints - basically a forked eyebrow, that is visible in one of the photos.     In the hour that we were there the bird showed amazing fidelity to one particular spot in the middle of the pond, returning to it over and over to feed in water that was about one inch deep., and defending his space. We watched him get chased around a bit by an aggressive avocet.  Our view was from 125'.  There are 23 previous records in California - all but one between July and December.  There is just one spring record in May 1991 on the Salton Sea.

The most striking diagnostic feature are the rich rufous edges on the tertials that are coming in, along with one or two rufous scapulars.  The feathers have a black shaft and rufous edging.  Otherwise the bird was much greyer than the Western Sandpipers.    The scapulars have a solid blackish appearance.  The face has a "split" supercilium that I understand distinguishes it from the other stints - basically a forked eyebrow, that is visible in one of the photos.     In the hour that we were there the bird showed amazing fidelity to one particular spot in the middle of the pond, returning to it over and over to feed in water that was about one inch deep., and defending his space. We watched him get chased around a bit by an aggressive avocet.  Our view was from 125'.  There are 23 previous records in California - all but one between July and December.  There is just one spring record in May 1991 on the Salton Sea.

I found this pale empid at 37.743747, -122.414228 on the north side of Bernal Hill.  At first seeing it in only silhouette I was struck by its long thin bill and long dark tail, thought I might be looking at a gnatcatcher for a second.  Walked around to the bare tree where it was perching in the back.  Bird seemed to stick around for a couple of minutes at a time and then disappear for 10-15 minutes.   Though I assumed Gray, I ended up walking up the hill and down a treacherous, but busy, footpath over the tree so I could get better documentation.   Uniformly gray head, auricular and back with no contrast.  Whitish throat and faint yellow on belly.   From certain angles the auricular patch seemed to stand out - the lores extensive white, and has distinctive white tuft at the base of upper mandible, which I understand helps separate Gray from Dusky.   The most definitive characteristic is the oversize thin bill, black upper mandible, yellow lower slightly darker at the tip.  If not for the size of the bill I think this would be hard to separate visually from Dusky.  Head is rounded with a slight hint of a peak to the back.   Wings and tail feathers have a weathered look in the photos with spread-wings - not sure where this would be in the molt cycle, doesn't seem complete.    Wings are comparatively short, with wingtips and rest not extending as far as undertail coverts.  Tail dark.  I think the size, shape, color of bill, length of wingtips, and head shape cinch this as a Gray vs. Hammonds/Dusky.  Bird gave out a soft "chewit"-like dry whit call.  Pumped tail downward a bit, but not excessively.  I did not use playback.  Bird did not strike me as being particularly larger than the other empids.

Noah Arthur and I were chatting on facebook this morning about searching for rarities along the Eastshore after the first rain of the fall. Then he goes out and quickly finds a first county record Mourning Warbler. I arrived at about 12:40pm and searched with him and Judi Sierra for about 40 minutes until we refound it. The bird is very secretive (like all MOWA as far as I know) and tended to stay in about a 100 ft radius of heavy riparian willow, thick clumps of grass and low branches.  Was feeding on the ground or lowest branches, never seen more than about 24" off the ground.  Did not allow particularly close approach. Juvenal plumage - presumed first year - sex indeterminate. Gray head, narrow white broken eye-ring "eye arcs" - fully broken by dark horizontal line.   The throat is off-white directly at the base of the lower mandible, but otherwise yellow.  Gray broken breast-band does not form a complete hood as MGWA (MacGillivray's) would.  Breast and underparts a convincing bright yellow that gave it an overall feel of n OCWA/. Tail seemed notably short.   Although 1st winter MOWA and MGWA are similar, I feel that the presence of yellow superloral, yellow throat, and thin eye arcs cinch the ID.  Bird behavior was also MOWA like, skulking and staying low to the ground or on dirt at all times. The creek makes up the county line.  When I arrived Noah had seen it on both sides of the creek (he initially found it bathing).  We refound it on the Contra Costa side where it stayed for about an hour - only allowing a few open views.  As I was leaving, Derek Heins refound the bird on the Alameda side, where it stayed at the water's edge for some time.

Pen-bird folks,  This afternoon around 2:30pm I found a good looking Tropical Kingbird at the Cypress Lawn Memorial Park in Colma.   The location was in the section of the cemetery that is south of El Camino Real, almost exactly where the Vermilion Flycatcher spent the winter of 2016-17.  This stretch is pretty birdy with flycatchers and thrushes.  The Tropical Kingbird was wide ranging, but came back several times to a perch near the top of a small yew(?) with dead branches on top.  He was also chased away a bit by the bluebirds, which were the only birds that seemed to mind his presence.  The yew tree was here 37.669597, -122.456826 though the flycatcher used the whole lawn.  Chris Hayward was nearby and we were able to refine the bird pretty quickly when he arrived.  Chris told me that Laurie Graham had one here in December, so I figure this bird has overwintered here.  Chris and I saw it fly off to the distance (toward the north), but I’ll bet it returns here frequently.

Observation Details: Found by Alvaro Jaramillo.  Seen from bluffs at Venice Beach looking over Francis Creek mouth.  Adult.  Appearance much like a Western Gull, perhaps a tiny bit smaller, much like the Herring Gulls it was associating with - back darker and 'slaty' than Western.  Legs more of a bubble-gum red and appear short. giving the bird a sleaker, shorter look than Western.  Head is streaky, with fine streaks, especailly around eye - yellow iris, only notable in direct sun.  Bill much thinner than Western, more like a Herring, with a small gonydial bump and small red gonys patch.  Bill is pale at the base with some yellow at the tip - but overall this is the most distinguishing differentiator from Western.

Very pale white belly and head, medium gray wings with some mottling (from a distance) but not the intricate feather pattern of a yellowlegs sp.   Seems to indicate some alternate plumage wing feathers coming in.  I wonder if this bird is molting-in-migration or if it has been here all winter.    The bird was not associating with other tringa, and seemed to squabble a few times with American Avocet.   Bird has an interesting side to side sweeping motion when foraging in shallow water, reminiscent of an Avocet.  Bill is needle thin and straight.  Long thin gray legs.  I have previously observed them in India and Ghana.

One flew from W side of harbor mouth to Jetty on E. Initially spotted by Peter Metropulos. Pished in for better views, and photos were taken. Overall a Savannah Sparrow with greyish tone to back, and very indistinct back streaking. No white "suspenders" on upperparts. Similarly underpart streaking dull and not as distinct as on typical Savannah. Overall a long-billed Savannah, but this was less noticeable than the lack of contrast in markings. Extremely rare in Northern California, but Pillar Point Harbor has become a place where sightings have occurred in the last few years. A first, a lifer, for Alvaro! Very exciting to see this from the boat!

Found on tree snag at corner of Devereux and Slough Roads at 2:10 PM.   Spotted by Aaron Maizlish, Jared Dawson, Kathleen Boehm-Dawson.   The bird was flycatching actively.  We observed it for about seven minutes, it moved perches several times.    It responded to Jared's playback, flying down and toward him.  Eventually flew out of sight into the willows to the East.  We were unable to refind him.  The flickr photos are geo-referenced to the exact tree where found.  Though unmistakable as an OS Flycatcher (look at the sharp vest) we wanted to rule out Greater Pewee.  Has two toned bill, which does not show well in photo -but more are available.

First SF record found by Hugh Cotter 10/9/17.  Small Sparrow sized-bird appeared very tame -  observed feeding for about 15 minutes on berm on the northern side of the great field.  Appears to be a young (first fall?) female.  Numerous field marks to separate from similar Chestnut-collared.  Note large pink bill with black tip.  Pale face with plain auriculars around unremarkable ear covert.  Wide pale supercilium - overall head color somewhat reminiscent of a female House Sparrow.  Bird had a buffy collar similar to head and not "chestnut.  Notable buffy breast-plate with barely any streaking coming to a crisp transition.  Breast patch remarkably similar in shape to that of the black breast patch of an adult male McCowns.  Median coverts were darker than other feathers - good field mark, though not as dark as an immature male, led me to think this is female.  Bird in flight had wide white patches on outer rectices.  Flew short-distances (20-50 meters) at low height - unlike a LALO.  Only called in flight.  This was my #600 ABA-Continental bird!

Locality: Alviso Marina County Park (please use a specific pond hotspot where possible)
Observation Details: The Little Stint was associating with a small group of Western Sandpipers and Dunlins, and not with Least Sandpipers.  It is about the size of a Least Sandpiper - considerably smaller than a Western.   The bill is short and slightly drooped with a distinct gape notch.   The legs are black and completely unwebbed (un-palmated).  They appear long relative to body size.  The most striking diagnostic feature are the rich rufous edges on the tertials that are coming in, along with one or two rufous scapulars.  The feathers have a black shaft and rufous edging.  Otherwise the bird was much greyer than the Western Sandpipers.    The scapulars have a solid blackish appearance.  The face has a "split" supercilium that I understand distinguishes it from the other stints - basically a forked eyebrow, that is visible in one of the photos.     In the hour that we were there the bird showed amazing fidelity to one particular spot in the middle of the pond, returning to it over and over to feed in water that was about one inch deep., and defending his space. We watched him get chased around a bit by an aggressive avocet.  Our view was from 125'.  There are 23 previous records in California - all but one between July and December.  There is just one spring record in May 1991 on the Salton Sea.

Continuing rarity.  Approximately the size of Lesser Yellowlegs but somewhat more slender.   Very pale white belly and head, medium gray wings with some mottling (from a distance) but not the intricate feather pattern of a yellowlegs sp.   Seems to indicate some alternate plumage wing feathers coming in.  I wonder if this bird is molting-in-migration or if it has been here all winter.    The bird was not associating with other tringa, and seemed to squabble a few times with American Avocet.   Bird has an interesting side to side sweeping motion when foraging in shallow water, reminiscent of an Avocet.  Bill is needle thin and straight.  Long thin gray legs.  I have previously observed them in India and Ghana.

I found this Blackburnian on the island at 2:33pm, in tall trees on the shore across from the Boat House - almost directly across the lake from where Nancy Palmer reported one this morning.  It was in a small flock of about 10 Yellow & Townsend's Warblers + 1 BTYW.   I was not able to get a good photo of it, and gave up as it worked its way higher into the cypresses.  But I did get good looks at it initially and also in flight, and was confident in my ID. Small warbler - similar to Townsend's but with a more compact elongated shape and a more direct flight style.  Head not as rounded as Townsend's.  Bird appears to be 1st winter.   Wide unbroken white wing bars and a black back that matched the wings, not gray (TOWA) or Green (CERW).  I did not get a good look at any detail "braces" on the back and the poor photos don't show anything, but the color was definitive.   Yellow wash extends unbroken acros the throat and breast almost to the legs.  Streaked on flanks, not excessively.   Head has the typical gray triangular auriculars of a Blackburnian, but not very well defined in the back, which was smudgy yellow and gray.   Defining feature is the lengthy yellow supercilium extending all the way to the nape, and the lower eye crescent that appears white in the photos.   Combination of all of these traits ufficient to eliminate TOWA.  A couple things bother me about this bird however.  The photos seem to show a long tail with extendsive black on the sides, which is somewhat forked, kind of like a Parula.   None of this looks typical for either BLWA nor TOWA.  Also the bird has a somewhat well defined eye arcs in one of the photos though that may be a trick of the angle.  Considered other species. Face pattern, black back and sharp white wing bar are all a good match for BLWA however.

Locality: Half Moon Bay SB--Venice Beach and Pilarcitos Creek Mouth
Observation Details: Found by Alvaro Jaramillo.  Seen from bluffs at Venice Beach looking over Francis Creek mouth.  Adult.  Appearance much like a Western Gull, perhaps a tiny bit smaller, much like the Herring Gulls it was associating with - back darker and 'slaty' than Western.  Legs more of a bubble-gum red and appear short. giving the bird a sleaker, shorter look than Western.  Head is streaky, with fine streaks, especailly around eye - yellow iris, only notable in direct sun.  Bill much thinner than Western, more like a Herring, with a small gonydial bump and small red gonys patch.  Bill is pale at the base with some yellow at the tip - but overall this is the most distinguishing differentiator from Western.

Noah Arthur and I were chatting on facebook this morning about searching for rarities along the Eastshore after the first rain of the fall. Then he goes out and quickly finds a first county record Mourning Warbler. I arrived at about 12:40pm and searched with him and Judi Sierra for about 40 minutes until we refound it. The bird is very secretive (like all MOWA as far as I know) and tended to stay in about a 100 ft radius of heavy riparian willow, thick clumps of grass and low branches.  Was feeding on the ground or lowest branches, never seen more than about 24" off the ground.  Did not allow particularly close approach. Juvenal plumage - presumed first year - sex indeterminate. Gray head, narrow white broken eye-ring "eye arcs" - fully broken by dark horizontal line.   The throat is off-white directly at the base of the lower mandible, but otherwise yellow.  Gray broken breast-band does not form a complete hood as MGWA (MacGillivray's) would.  Breast and underparts a convincing bright yellow that gave it an overall feel of n OCWA/. Tail seemed notably short.   Although 1st winter MOWA and MGWA are similar, I feel that the presence of yellow superloral, yellow throat, and thin eye arcs cinch the ID.  Bird behavior was also MOWA like, skulking and staying low to the ground or on dirt at all times. The creek makes up the county line.  When I arrived Noah had seen it on both sides of the creek (he initially found it bathing).  We refound it on the Contra Costa side where it stayed for about an hour - only allowing a few open views.  As I was leaving, Derek Heins refound the bird on the Alameda side, where it stayed at the water's edge for some time.

Observation Details: 1st year bird in crisp juvenal plumage.   Found at about 9:45 am, as seen from the wood pedestrian bridge.  On the island with approximately 1,000 Elegant Terns - but more associated with a few Least Sandpipers and staying away from the terns.  Medium-sized shorebird, larger than pectoral, small than knot.   Had a very dumpy posture, not uncommon for juveniles, almost like a Green Heron when its head is down.   Bold, plain dark scapular feathers - which is the first thing I notice with Ruffs, with wide buffy fringes, all feathers appearing even aged.  Head and neck were dull buff color, no streaking on breast or belly.  Thin dark slightly-decurved "Dunlin-type" bill.  Dull green-yellow  "Willet-like" legs.  Head appears small for body, giving a hunched appearance when feeding.  Floppy rear wing feathers (extended tertials?) also diagnostic.

Locality: Pelagic. Island Packers. Leg 7. 33.60863 -119.66825. Bearing SSE
Observation Details: At approximately 12:37 as we were sneaking up on the big storm-petrel flock, a large storm-petrel quartered in towards the bow from the right. It was called out that “a close storm-petrel” was in front of the boat so those on the bow could get photos and identify it. The consensus of some in the bow was a dark-rumped Leach's, but they were troubled by some of the field marks. A dark-rumped chapmani Leach’s was trailing the bird in question so that may have caused some confusion. Those birds passed the bow quickly.  The bird was gone so fast as storm-petrels do and we were approaching the large flock so we were on to the next thing. Upon reviewing photos the following day, David Pereksta was alarmed when he saw the details of this bird and suspected it could be a Tristram's Storm-Petrel.  A robust-looking sooty-colored storm-petrel with pale back and rump, deeply forked tail, bright carpal bars, and contrastingly dark head. In addition, other photos show it apparently gliding on slightly bowed wings. The underside was uniformly dark including the underwings. The carpal bars were very pale at the base along the inner trailing edge of the wings, indicating a fresh juvenile. The primary shafts appeared bare, but this species has dark shafts that can reflect silvery under certain lighting conditions. Joel Barrett’s photos with the Leach’s in the same frame show a shocking size difference with the bird in question being much larger and more robust. The overwhelming consensus of seabird experts consulted is that the bird is a Tristram's Storm-Petrel.  This bird was seen 19 nautical miles NNW from San Nicolas island (GPS coordinates: 33,35,20.88000, 119,38,51.79200).
I spent most of the hour photographing them.  All together at distance of 20-30’.

Observation Details: Refound it after an absence of 1 hour+.   Alone.  Dull-brown 'dusky' back and crown, light unstreaked chin and breast, some faint warm ochre tones on underbelly.  Defined white supercilium and under-eye subloral with a smudgy black eye line extending far back. The supercilium  becoming buff behind the lores.   Short thin bill.  Legs are orange-red.   Would forage low in the thicker bushes, preferring shade and then fly 50-100 yards at a time.  Always seemed to 'tink' a few times before taking flight, and sometimes while in the air.

Tern in with the Forster's Terns at the shoreline.  Full black cap in breeding plumage - still possible for Common in Nov., highly unusual for Forster's.  I took this to be a Common because of the full cap, the shape of the cap behind the eye, the thin reddish bill with the black tip, and the slightly squattish posture compared to the other terns (though this was hard to gauge).  Feedback from Alvaro says that it might be unidentifiable from this photo, but he leans to an aberrant Forster's, esp. based on color of bill and legs.  Would be nice to see it closer up.

I found this Blackburnian on the island at 2:33pm, in tall trees on the shore across from the Boat House - almost directly across the lake from where Nancy Palmer reported one this morning.  It was in a small flock of about 10 Yellow & Townsend's Warblers + 1 BTYW.   I was not able to get a good photo of it, and gave up as it worked its way higher into the cypresses.  But I did get good looks at it initially and also in flight, and was confident in my ID. Small warbler - similar to Townsend's but with a more compact elongated shape and a more direct flight style.  Head not as rounded as Townsend's.  Bird appears to be 1st winter.   Wide unbroken white wing bars and a black back that matched the wings, not gray (TOWA) or Green (CERW).  I did not get a good look at any detail "braces" on the back and the poor photos don't show anything, but the color was definitive.   Yellow wash extends unbroken acros the throat and breast almost to the legs.  Streaked on flanks, not excessively.   Head has the typical gray triangular auriculars of a Blackburnian, but not very well defined in the back, which was smudgy yellow and gray.   Defining feature is the lengthy yellow supercilium extending all the way to the nape, and the lower eye crescent that appears white in the photos.   Combination of all of these traits ufficient to eliminate TOWA.  A couple things bother me about this bird however.  The photos seem to show a long tail with extendsive black on the sides, which is somewhat forked, kind of like a Parula.   None of this looks typical for either BLWA nor TOWA.  Also the bird has a somewhat well defined eye arcs in one of the photos though that may be a trick of the angle.  Considered other species. Face pattern, black back and sharp white wing bar are all a good match for BLWA however.

Found by William Legge this morning.  Staked out for 1.5 hrs before refound.  On the shoreline, north side of lagoon in an area with some green algae wrack and grasses.  Hard to see, only came out for seconds at a time before retreating into deep marsh grass.  Seen well in flight twice with long tail with wel defined white outer rectices - very much like a White Wagtail in flight, though longer tail.  Head pattern is diffuse gray auriculars with gray extending to nape (no white crescent behind auricular patch as you would expect with an HY Citrine Wagtail.)  I do not know how to separate Eastern and Western Yellow Wagtail by sight.  Only gave off a few single pip calls in flight, no repeated song.

I have previously observed them in India and Ghana.

Locality: Alviso Marina County Park (please use a specific pond hotspot where possible)
Observation Details: The Little Stint was associating with a small group of Western Sandpipers and Dunlins, and not with Least Sandpipers.  It is about the size of a Least Sandpiper - considerably smaller than a Western.   The bill is short and slightly drooped with a distinct gape notch.   The legs are black and completely unwebbed (un-palmated).  They appear long relative to body size.  The most striking diagnostic feature are the rich rufous edges on the tertials that are coming in, along with one or two rufous scapulars.  The feathers have a black shaft and rufous edging.  Otherwise the bird was much greyer than the Western Sandpipers.    The scapulars have a solid blackish appearance.  The face has a "split" supercilium that I understand distinguishes it from the other stints - basically a forked eyebrow, that is visible in one of the photos.     In the hour that we were there the bird showed amazing fidelity to one particular spot in the middle of the pond, returning to it over and over to feed in water that was about one inch deep., and defending his space. We watched him get chased around a bit by an aggressive avocet.  Our view was from 125'.  There are 23 previous records in California - all but one between July and December.  There is just one spring record in May 1991 on the Salton Sea.

Locality: Bodega Head - offshore species and the bluff ONLY
Observation Details: Continuing. Life bird for me.  A lot like a Purple Sandpiper - a bit duller in color.  Associating with Surfbirds - similar color scheme, chevroned breast and flanks, tended to blend in with the sea rocks.   Smaller than a Black Turnstone, thinner and longer - bill is thin and decurved, yellow at the base (not always evident) - scaly pattern distinctive, dark secondaries with white fringe - one rufous (summer) scapular remaining.  Took about 20 minutes to find, I observed for about 30 minutes, spent most of the time with his head tucked in.  Very compatible with SURF and BLTU.

SF Folks,  On Monday Lee Guichan posted about a possible Red-naped Sapsucker at North Lake, and the description that she sent me offline sounded interesting enough. I finally made my way over to Golden Gate Park yesterday (Friday) afternoon.  Fortunately I ran into Lee and she pointed me right too it - its working a small tree about 30' upslope from the trail about 150' north of the bridge in the SW side of the lake.  Very easy to miss, but judging by the sap wells it's been working this tree for a while.  The bird was calm and did not move much.  The back is extensively barred with a lot of white - and the breast and belly are creamy-white with no trace of red.  The head is stripy with a broad continuous white malar (if that's what it's called on a woodpecker) continuing to the breast, and a white supercilium that continues back to the nape.   The red nuchal patch is connected to the red head, with only one black spot above it, rather than the discontinuous red patch on a pure RNSA.   The throat is red with an indistinct black border.   The only thing I see not favoring pure-RNSA is the amount of red on the back of the head (and maybe the lack of black on the neck which I didn't see well), but I don't know if this is outside normal variation for RNSA, as the body seems to match RNSA.  I'd welcome expert opinion on this.

Observation Details: Recently fledged young bird.  Family reported earlier in the day, did not see adults.  I got down to the Presidio around 5pm this evening.  With David Tomb, we were able to pretty quickly get on what appears to be a recently fledged Lawrence’s Goldfinch.  (Someone please correct me if I’m wrong!). Note the white in the tail, the yellow already coming in on the wing, the pale head and large bill - all of which I think safely separate this from the other finches.  We stayed with this bird for about ten minutes and then it flew off with another (possibly juvenile, possibly adult female.). This was at the coordinates that Lee Hong-Chang gave in the first post.  Over the next hour I was unable to get on any other LAGOs - though I heard the tinkle call a few times.  It was difficult with the high winds and the literally hundred plus House Finch, Lesser Goldfinch, juncos, song and WC sparrows, and Hooded Orioles flying around.  This area seems to be a breeding frenzy.   You should also check the trees in a little gully about 100 yards north of the spot (not accessible by any main trail) where I last heard the LAGO call.  Are there any other breeding records of this bird in San Francisco in modern times?

This area seems to be a breeding frenzy.   You should also check the trees in a little gully about 100 yards north of the spot (not accessible by any main trail) where I last heard the LAGO call.  Are there any other breeding records of this bird in San Francisco in modern times?

Two hawks were flying north as I was arriving on the hill - heading over Mission Dolores.  One was an obvious RTHA, the second a small buteo that I immediately took to be a Broad-winged.  Tail had barring on both top and bottom.  Smaller compared to RTHA with elongated tail, and seemed to have shorter wings with definitive bulge.  In flight the top of the tail had wide dark bands (not in photo), and the belly was very white.  Was almost out of sight by the time I had my camera out, but I think the photos should be sufficient.    Expert opinion that this is actually a Cooper's Hawk.

Locality: Half Moon Bay SB--Venice Beach and Pilarcitos Creek Mouth
Observation Details: Found by Alvaro Jaramillo.  Seen from bluffs at Venice Beach looking over Francis Creek mouth.  Adult.  Appearance much like a Western Gull, perhaps a tiny bit smaller, much like the Herring Gulls it was associating with - back darker and 'slaty' than Western.  Legs more of a bubble-gum red and appear short. giving the bird a sleaker, shorter look than Western.  Head is streaky, with fine streaks, especailly around eye - yellow iris, only notable in direct sun.  Bill much thinner than Western, more like a Herring, with a small gonydial bump and small red gonys patch.  Bill is pale at the base with some yellow at the tip - but overall this is the most distinguishing differentiator from Western.

On the abandoned pier next to the old Coast Guard station at Crissy Field with DC Cormorants and Gulls.  Reported earlier in the day by Peter Winch to the park staff.  From afar I got a good view of the head, but by the time I got up to the pier the booby was back asleep with its head tucked in for the 15 minutes duration I was able to get close views.   Young (1st/2nd year?) booby with cafe-latte colored chest, belly, scaps and darker primaries and tail - about the size of a cormorant but somewhat lighter.  Bill a fleshy dull pink color, notably bright red and extremely short legs.  Never moved while I was photographing it.  I believe this is 2nd city record.

Light morph appeared at 11:30 - close-in, dropped below cliffs and resighted about 10 minutes later by Jonah B., at his house about 1/4 mile south.    Adult appeared at 11:39am and on and off again for about 45 minutes - initially tried to cross the gate (northward) in a very heavy wind and got dangerously close to water about half way across.  Came back to the Presidio and hung around for a while, occasionally harassed by a Red-Tailed Hawk and by the crows.  Last seen gaining elevation north of Fort Scott in what seemed to be a second attempt to cross.  My guess is that it blew too far south in the 75 mph winds and was trying to reposition northward.

Noah Arthur and I were chatting on facebook this morning about searching for rarities along the Eastshore after the first rain of the fall. Then he goes out and quickly finds a first county record Mourning Warbler. I arrived at about 12:40pm and searched with him and Judi Sierra for about 40 minutes until we refound it. The bird is very secretive (like all MOWA as far as I know) and tended to stay in about a 100 ft radius of heavy riparian willow, thick clumps of grass and low branches.  Was feeding on the ground or lowest branches, never seen more than about 24" off the ground.  Did not allow particularly close approach. Juvenal plumage - presumed first year - sex indeterminate. Gray head, narrow white broken eye-ring "eye arcs" - fully broken by dark horizontal line.   The throat is off-white directly at the base of the lower mandible, but otherwise yellow.  Gray broken breast-band does not form a complete hood as MGWA (MacGillivray's) would.  Breast and underparts a convincing bright yellow that gave it an overall feel of n OCWA/. Tail seemed notably short.   Although 1st winter MOWA and MGWA are similar, I feel that the presence of yellow superloral, yellow throat, and thin eye arcs cinch the ID.  Bird behavior was also MOWA like, skulking and staying low to the ground or on dirt at all times. The creek makes up the county line.  When I arrived Noah had seen it on both sides of the creek (he initially found it bathing).  We refound it on the Contra Costa side where it stayed for about an hour - only allowing a few open views.  As I was leaving, Derek Heins refound the bird on the Alameda side, where it stayed at the water's edge for some time.

Locality: Pelagic. Island Packers. Leg 12. 33.79379 -119.17798. Bearing N
Pelagic. Island Packers. Leg 7. 33.60863 -119.66825. Bearing SSE
Observation Details: The Wedge-rumped Storm-Petrel was discovered in photos of the large Black and Ashy Storm-Petrel flock at 12:39. Some may have seen the bird as it lifted up from the far-left side of the flock and several photographers discovered the bird in their images; most notably Aaron Maizlish and Larry Sansone. This bird was noticeable smaller than the other storm-petrels. The bird was black and appeared to be in heavy wing molt. A large triangular white rump patch extending almost to the end of the tail was evident, unlike the rump of a Townsend's. The bird also had a short thick bill, steep forehead, and no pronounced carpal bars. The deep wingbeats in the photos are also consistent with Wedge-rumped. Upon reviewing the photos, Steve Howell noted that the molting wings are consistent with Wedge-rumped at this season; this molt is not typical of Townsend’s at this season. The consensus among several of the leaders and other seabird experts that were consulted in the following days was that this individual was indeed a Wedge-rumped Storm-Petrel. This bird was in view for only a few seconds and was gone quickly as the flock dispersed.  This bird was seen 19 nautical miles NNW from San Nicolas island (GPS coordinates: 33,35,7.2240, 119,38,39.92399).
